    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.77-78_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">77</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Sunday <hi rend="underline">pm</hi></dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>We are all so delighted. I immediately wrote <hi rend="caps">M.B.</hi>Dickson, MildredNye<sic>Mildred Nye</sic> Dewey, and spread the joyous news, but forgot to promptly send you a "Thank you."</p>
                
                <p>I even told the <hi rend="caps">K.C.</hi>Star, but we are not fully organized yet, and lacking two officers, I hesitated to put in the part we had.</p>
                
                <p>Just returned from Springfield --Drury Writers Meet. Was good and I always carry away big ideas from these meetings, generally to be lost in the heydey of living. I met Edsel Ford; he's a nice person.</p>
                
                <p>I sent for your book the day I got your letter. All this time since I met you and little wife at Emporia, I menat to hav<del/><add>e</add> it. My friend Vaun Arnold (perhs<del>p</del><add>a</add>s<sic>perhaps</sic> you knew he passed on last Easter Day) well he was a fan of yours. He wrote such heavenly poetry, much on the Western type.</p>
                
                <p>Spring days here again make me want to burst out into something like a plum tree or a crocus bed, I feel that I just am going to do something rare these rare days, but alas all day I toiled, I mean toiled, yes, on Sunday. Cou<del>o</del><add>l</add>d get help on the work on Sabbath, so I worked.</p>
                
                <p>Work is so invigorating. I have found this office has much work attached to it, too. But think finally it will strike "pay dirt."</p>
                
                <p>Must close now, wishing you the best of all things. After corresponding with Margarette Ball Dickson, I find it good business to drag<del>e</del> out all the superlatives and sun them. She does. Don't quote me on t<unclear>h</unclear>is, but think she said you are the best living poet of English people. (Did she think there might be a better one, eh, of non-English speech?)</p>
                
                <p>Ta, ta, now.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
